# SKILL — Stripe Payment Link + PDF Delivery on Netlify

## When to use this skill
Use whenever adding a new paid PDF product to the main site (aievolvingyou.com). This covers the full pattern from Stripe to download.

---

## The full pattern

### 1. Add the PDF to the repo
```bash
cp "/path/to/YourProduct.pdf" public/downloads/Your-Product-Name.pdf
git add public/downloads/
git commit -m "Add [product name] PDF to downloads"
git push
```

**Critical:** Verify the file is a real PDF before committing:
```bash
file public/downloads/Your-Product-Name.pdf
# Must return: PDF document, version X.X, N pages
```

**Critical:** Verify Git actually has the right content:
```bash
git show HEAD:public/downloads/Your-Product-Name.pdf | file -
# Must return: PDF document
```

---

### 2. Add the Content-Disposition header to netlify.toml

Add a new `[[headers]]` block for each PDF. The catch-all redirect must remain LAST:

```toml
[build]
  command = "npm run build"
  publish = "dist"

[[headers]]
  for = "/downloads/AI-Procurement-Questions-for-Hiring-Teams.pdf"
    [headers.values]
      Content-Disposition = "attachment; filename=AI-Procurement-Questions-for-Hiring-Teams.pdf"

[[headers]]
  for = "/downloads/Your-New-Product.pdf"
    [headers.values]
      Content-Disposition = "attachment; filename=Your-New-Product.pdf"

[[redirects]]
  from = "/*"
  to = "/index.html"
  status = 200
```

**Why this matters:** The `/* → /index.html` catch-all intercepts ALL requests including static files. Without the headers block, browsers receive an HTML page instead of a PDF, which corrupts the download.

---

### 3. Create the ThankYou component

File location: `src/components/ThankYou[ProductName].jsx`

Copy `ThankYou.jsx` as the template and update:
- The product name in the heading and description
- The `href` on the download button — must match exactly the filename in `public/downloads/`
- The `download` attribute value — the filename the user sees when saving
- The page metadata text (categories, page count etc)

**Critical:** The `href` must use hyphens and match the exact filename in `public/downloads/`. A single character mismatch causes a 404.

---

### 4. Wire the route in App.jsx

Add import:
```js
import ThankYouProductName from "./components/ThankYouProductName";
```

Add route (before `</Routes>`):
```jsx
<Route path="/thank-you/product-slug" element={<ThankYouProductName />} />
```

---

### 5. Set up Stripe

**Payment Link settings:**
- After payment → Don't show confirmation page → Redirect to: `https://aievolvingyou.com/thank-you/product-slug`
- Advanced options → Allow promotion codes: ON

**Discount codes:**
- Product catalogue → Coupons → Create coupon (set the discount rule)
- Click into the coupon → Promotion codes section → click `+` → create the code customers type
- Both must exist. Coupon alone = "This code is invalid" at checkout.

---

### 6. Verify before launch checklist

- [ ] `file public/downloads/[name].pdf` returns "PDF document"
- [ ] `git show HEAD:public/downloads/[name].pdf | file -` returns "PDF document"  
- [ ] `ls dist/downloads/` after `npm run build` shows the file at correct size
- [ ] Direct URL `https://aievolvingyou.com/downloads/[name].pdf` opens PDF in incognito browser
- [ ] Download button on thank-you page downloads correct file
- [ ] Stripe redirect URL is set correctly in Payment Link settings
- [ ] Promotion code exists inside the coupon (not just the coupon alone)

---

## Known gotchas

**iCloud file stubs:** Files stored in iCloud may show correct size locally but be stubs (not fully downloaded). Always verify with `file` command and `git show HEAD | file -` before assuming the commit is correct.

**Browser cache:** When testing downloads, use incognito/private mode to bypass cache. The `-2`, `-3` suffixes on downloaded filenames indicate the browser is serving cached versions.

**Netlify cache:** After fixing file issues, always use "Deploy project without cache" in Netlify dashboard to force a full rebuild.

**Same URL can't both download and open inline:** The `Content-Disposition: attachment` header applies to the URL, not the link. If you need both a download button and an "open in browser" link, they must point to different URLs or the fallback link should be removed entirely.